Self-Hosting with Docker
Learn how to configure and deploy Supabase with Docker.

Docker is the easiest way to get started with self-hosted Supabase. It should only take you a few minutes to get up and running. This guide assumes you are running the command from the machine you intend to host from.
Contents#

    Before you begin
    Installing and running Supabase
    Accessing your services
    Updating your services
    Securing your services

Before you begin#

You need the following installed in your system: Git and Docker (Windows, MacOS, or Linux).
Installing and running Supabase#

Follow these steps to start Supabase on your machine:
# Get the code
git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/supabase/supabase

# Go to the docker folder
cd supabase/docker

# Copy the fake env vars
cp .env.example .env

# Pull the latest images
docker compose pull

# Start the services (in detached mode)
docker compose up -d

If you are using rootless docker, edit .env and set DOCKER_SOCKET_LOCATION to your docker socket location. For example: /run/user/1000/docker.sock. Otherwise, you will see an error like container supabase-vector exited (0).

After all the services have started you can see them running in the background:
docker compose ps

All of the services should have a status running (healthy). If you see a status like created but not running, try starting that service manually with docker compose start <service-name>.

Your app is now running with default credentials. Please secure your services as soon as possible using the instructions below.
Accessing Supabase Studio#

You can access Supabase Studio through the API gateway on port 8000. For example: http://<your-ip>:8000, or localhost:8000 if you are running Docker locally.

You will be prompted for a username and password. By default, the credentials are:

    Username: supabase
    Password: this_password_is_insecure_and_should_be_updated

You should change these credentials as soon as possible using the instructions below.
Accessing the APIs#

Each of the APIs are available through the same API gateway:

    REST: http://<your-ip>:8000/rest/v1/
    Auth: http://<your-domain>:8000/auth/v1/
    Storage: http://<your-domain>:8000/storage/v1/
    Realtime: http://<your-domain>:8000/realtime/v1/

Accessing your Edge Functions#

Edge Functions are stored in volumes/functions. The default setup has a hello Function that you can invoke on http://<your-domain>:8000/functions/v1/hello.

You can add new Functions as volumes/functions/<FUNCTION_NAME>/index.ts. Restart the functions service to pick up the changes: docker compose restart functions --no-deps
Accessing Postgres#

By default, the Supabase stack runs the Supavisor connection pooler. Supavisor provides efficient management of database connections.

You can connect to the Postgres database using the following methods:

    For session-based connections (equivalent to direct PostgreSQL connections):

psql 'postgres://postgres.your-tenant-id:your-super-secret-and-long-postgres-password@localhost:5432/postgres'

    For pooled transactional connections:

psql 'postgres://postgres.your-tenant-id:your-super-secret-and-long-postgres-password@localhost:6543/postgres'

The default tenant ID is your-tenant-id, and the default password is your-super-secret-and-long-postgres-password. You should change these as soon as possible using the instructions below.

By default, the database is not accessible from outside the local machine but the pooler is. You can change this by updating the docker-compose.yml file.
Updating your services#

For security reasons, we "pin" the versions of each service in the docker-compose file (these versions are updated ~monthly). If you want to update any services immediately, you can do so by updating the version number in the docker compose file and then running docker compose pull. You can find all the latest docker images in the Supabase Docker Hub.

You should update your services frequently to get the latest features and bug fixes and security patches. Note that you will need to restart the services to pick up the changes, which will result in some downtime for your services.

Example
You'll want to update the Studio(Dashboard) frequently to get the latest features and bug fixes. To update the Dashboard:

    Visit the supabase/studio image in the Supabase Docker Hub
    Find the latest version (tag) number. It will look something like 20241029-46e1e40
    Update the image field in the docker-compose.yml file to the new version. It should look like this: image: supabase/studio:20241028-a265374
    Run docker compose pull and then docker compose up -d to restart the service with the new version.

Securing your services#

While we provided you with some example secrets for getting started, you should NEVER deploy your Supabase setup using the defaults we have provided. Please follow all of the steps in this section to ensure you have a secure setup, and then restart all services to pick up the changes.
Generate API keys#

We need to generate secure keys for accessing your services. We'll use the JWT Secret to generate anon and service API keys using the form below.

    Obtain a Secret: Use the 40-character secret provided, or create your own. If creating, ensure it's a strong, random string of 40 characters.
    Store Securely: Save the secret in a secure location on your local machine. Don't share this secret publicly or commit it to version control.
    Generate a JWT: Use the form below to generate a new JWT using your secret.

JWT Secret:

Key:

The JWT will be generated from this info:
{
  "role": "anon",
  "iss": "supabase",
  "iat": 1737187200,
  "exp": 1894953600
}

Update API keys#

Run this form twice to generate new anon and service API keys. Replace the values in the ./docker/.env file:

    ANON_KEY - replace with an anon key
    SERVICE_ROLE_KEY - replace with a service key

You will need to restart the services for the changes to take effect.
Update secrets#

Update the ./docker/.env file with your own secrets. In particular, these are required:

    POSTGRES_PASSWORD: the password for the postgres role.
    JWT_SECRET: used by PostgREST and GoTrue, among others.
    SITE_URL: the base URL of your site.
    SMTP_*: mail server credentials. You can use any SMTP server.
    POOLER_TENANT_ID: the tenant-id that will be used by supavisor pooler for your connection string

You will need to restart the services for the changes to take effect.
Dashboard authentication#

The Dashboard is protected with basic authentication. The default user and password MUST be updated before using Supabase in production.
Update the following values in the ./docker/.env file:

    DASHBOARD_USERNAME: The default username for the Dashboard
    DASHBOARD_PASSWORD: The default password for the Dashboard

You can also add more credentials for multiple users in ./docker/volumes/api/kong.yml. For example:
docker/volumes/api/kong.yml
basicauth_credentials:
- consumer: DASHBOARD
  username: user_one
  password: password_one
- consumer: DASHBOARD
  username: user_two
  password: password_two

You will need to restart the services for the changes to take effect.
Restarting all services#

You can restart services to pick up any configuration changes by running:
# Stop and remove the containers
docker compose down

# Recreate and start the containers
docker compose up -d

Be aware that this will result in downtime. Simply restarting the services does not apply configuration changes.
Stopping all services#

You can stop Supabase by running docker compose stop in same directory as your docker-compose.yml file.
Uninstalling#

You can stop Supabase by running the following in same directory as your docker-compose.yml file:
# Stop docker and remove volumes:
docker compose down -v

# Remove Postgres data:
rm -rf volumes/db/data/

This will destroy all data in the database and storage volumes, so be careful!
Managing your secrets#

Many components inside Supabase use secure secrets and passwords. These are listed in the self-hosting env file, but we strongly recommend using a secrets manager when deploying to production. Plain text files like dotenv lead to accidental costly leaks.

Some suggested systems include:

    Doppler
    Infisical
    Key Vault by Azure (Microsoft)
    Secrets Manager by AWS
    Secrets Manager by GCP
    Vault by Hashicorp

Advanced#

Everything beyond this point in the guide helps you understand how the system works and how you can modify it to suit your needs.
Architecture#

Supabase is a combination of open source tools, each specifically chosen for Enterprise-readiness.

If the tools and communities already exist, with an MIT, Apache 2, or equivalent open license, we will use and support that tool.
If the tool doesn't exist, we build and open source it ourselves.
Diagram showing the architecture of Supabase. The Kong API gateway sits in front of 7 services: GoTrue, PostgREST, Realtime, Storage, pg_meta, Functions, and pg_graphql. All the services talk to a single Postgres instance.

    Kong is a cloud-native API gateway.
    GoTrue is an JWT based API for managing users and issuing JWT tokens.
    PostgREST is a web server that turns your PostgreSQL database directly into a RESTful API
    Realtime is an Elixir server that allows you to listen to PostgreSQL inserts, updates, and deletes using websockets. Realtime polls Postgres' built-in replication functionality for database changes, converts changes to JSON, then broadcasts the JSON over websockets to authorized clients.
    Storage provides a RESTful interface for managing Files stored in S3, using Postgres to manage permissions.
    postgres-meta is a RESTful API for managing your Postgres, allowing you to fetch tables, add roles, and run queries, etc.
    PostgreSQL is an object-relational database system with over 30 years of active development that has earned it a strong reputation for reliability, feature robustness, and performance.
    Supavisor is a scalable connection pooler for Postgres, allowing for efficient management of database connections.

For the system to work cohesively, some services require additional configuration within the Postgres database. For example, the APIs and Auth system require several default roles and the pgjwt Postgres extension.

You can find all the default extensions inside the schema migration scripts repo. These scripts are mounted at /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d to run automatically when starting the database container.
Configuring services#

Each system has a number of configuration options which can be found in the relevant product documentation.

    Postgres
    PostgREST
    Realtime
    Auth
    Storage
    Kong
    Supavisor

These configuration items are generally added to the env section of each service, inside the docker-compose.yml section. If these configuration items are sensitive, they should be stored in a secret manager or using an .env file and then referenced using the ${} syntax.
docker-compose.yml
.env
services:
 rest:
   image: postgrest/postgrest
   environment:
     PGRST_JWT_SECRET: ${JWT_SECRET}
Common configuration#

Each system can be configured independently. Some of the most common configuration options are listed below.
Configuring an email server#

You will need to use a production-ready SMTP server for sending emails. You can configure the SMTP server by updating the following environment variables:
.env
SMTP_ADMIN_EMAIL=
SMTP_HOST=
SMTP_PORT=
SMTP_USER=
SMTP_PASS=
SMTP_SENDER_NAME=

We recommend using AWS SES. It's extremely cheap and reliable. Restart all services to pick up the new configuration.
Configuring S3 Storage#

By default all files are stored locally on the server. You can configure the Storage service to use S3 by updating the following environment variables:
docker-compose.yml
  storage:
    environment:
      STORAGE_BACKEND=s3
      GLOBAL_S3_BUCKET=name-of-your-s3-bucket
      REGION=region-of-your-s3-bucket

You can find all the available options in the storage repository. Restart the storage service to pick up the changes: docker compose restart storage --no-deps
Configuring Supabase AI Assistant#

Configuring the Supabase AI Assistant is optional. By adding your own OPENAI_API_KEY, you can enable AI services, which help with writing SQL queries, statements, and policies.
docker-compose.yml
.env
services:
  studio:
    image: supabase/studio
    environment:
      OPENAI_API_KEY: ${OPENAI_API_KEY:-}
Setting database's log_min_messages#

By default, docker compose sets the database's log_min_messages configuration to fatal to prevent redundant logs generated by Realtime. You can configure log_min_messages using any of the Postgres Severity Levels.
Accessing Postgres through Supavisor#

By default, the Postgres database is accessible through the Supavisor connection pooler. This allows for more efficient management of database connections. You can connect to the pooled database using the POOLER_PROXY_PORT_TRANSACTION port and POSTGRES_PORT for session based connections.

For more information on configuring and using Supavisor, see the Supavisor documentation.
Exposing your Postgres database#

If you need direct access to the Postgres database without going through Supavisor, you can expose it by updating the docker-compose.yml file:
docker-compose.yml
# Comment or remove the supavisor section of the docker-compose file
#  supavisor:
#    ports:
# ...
  db:
    ports:
      - ${POSTGRES_PORT}:${POSTGRES_PORT}

This is less-secure, so please make sure you are running a firewall in front of your server.
File storage backend on macOS#

By default, Storage backend is set to file, which is to use local files as the storage backend. For macOS compatibility, you need to choose VirtioFS as the Docker container file sharing implementation (in Docker Desktop -> Preferences -> General).
Setting up logging with the Analytics server#

Additional configuration is required for self-hosting the Analytics server. For the full setup instructions, see Self Hosting Analytics.
Upgrading Analytics#

Due to the changes in the Analytics server, you will need to run the following commands to upgrade your Analytics server:

All data in analytics will be deleted when you run the commands below.
### Destroy analytics to transition to postgres self hosted solution without other data loss

# Enter the container and use your .env POSTGRES_PASSWORD value to login
docker exec -it $(docker ps | grep supabase-db | awk '{print $1}') psql -U supabase_admin --password
# Drop all the data in the _analytics schema
DROP PUBLICATION logflare_pub; DROP SCHEMA _analytics CASCADE; CREATE SCHEMA _analytics;\q
# Drop the analytics container
docker rm supabase-analytics
Demo#

A minimal setup working on Ubuntu, hosted on DigitalOcean.
Demo using DigitalOcean#

    A DigitalOcean Droplet with 1 GB memory and 25 GB solid-state drive (SSD) is sufficient to start
    To access the Dashboard, use the ipv4 IP address of your Droplet.
    If you're unable to access Dashboard, run docker compose ps to see if the Studio service is running and healthy.

Below is a straightforward guide to help you get Supabase running on an Ubuntu server using Docker. This tutorial will walk you through installing Docker, cloning the Supabase repository, bringing the containers online, and securing the default configuration.

---

## 1. Prerequisites

- **Ubuntu Server**: Make sure you have a running Ubuntu server and SSH access to it.
- **Docker**: Installed on your Ubuntu server.
- **Git**: Installed on your Ubuntu server.

If you need to install Docker and Git on a fresh Ubuntu machine, follow these steps:

```bash
# Update the package list
sudo apt update

# Install Git
sudo apt install -y git

# Install Docker
# On modern versions of Ubuntu, you can get Docker from the official Docker repos
sudo apt install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg

# Add Docker’s official GPG key
sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

# Set up the repository
echo \
  "deb [arch=$(dpkg --print-architecture) signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] \
  https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu \
  $(lsb_release -cs) stable" | \
  sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list > /dev/null

# Update and install Docker Engine
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin

# Check Docker version
docker --version

# (Optional) If you want to run Docker without sudo, add your user to the docker group:
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
# Then log out and back in so that your group membership is re-evaluated.
```

---

## 2. Clone the Supabase Repository

We’ll pull the official **supabase** repository with a depth of 1 to keep it minimal:

```bash
git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/supabase/supabase
cd supabase/docker
```

---

## 3. Copy and Configure Environment Variables

Inside the `supabase/docker` directory, there is an example environment file called `.env.example`. Copy it to `.env` and review or edit the values as needed:

```bash
cp .env.example .env
```

> **Note**: The `.env` file contains default credentials and secrets that must be changed before going to production.

Some important variables you should consider changing immediately:

- `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`
- `JWT_SECRET`
- `SITE_URL`
- `POOLER_TENANT_ID`
- `ANON_KEY` and `SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`
- `DASHBOARD_USERNAME` and `DASHBOARD_PASSWORD` (the login for Supabase Studio)

---

## 4. Pull the Supabase Docker Images

To ensure that we have the latest images:

```bash
docker compose pull
```

This will download all of the required Supabase service images to your system.

---

## 5. Start the Supabase Services

Now, bring up the entire Supabase stack using Docker Compose:

```bash
docker compose up -d
```

Docker Compose will start the following services in the background:

1. **Kong** (API Gateway)
2. **PostgREST** (auto-generated REST API)
3. **GoTrue** (Auth service)
4. **Realtime** (WebSocket for database changes)
5. **Storage** (Object storage and file management)
6. **Supavisor** (Connection pooler)
7. **PostgreSQL** (Database)
8. **Studio** (Dashboard/UI)
9. **Analytics** (Optional; collects logs)

Check their status with:

```bash
docker compose ps
```

All services should eventually show `running (healthy)`. If any container is stuck in a non-running state, you can start it manually:

```bash
docker compose start <service-name>
```

---

## 6. Access Supabase Studio

By default, Supabase Studio is exposed on **port 8000**. Open your browser and navigate to:

```
http://<YOUR_SERVER_IP>:8000
```

> **Default Credentials**
>
> - **Username**: `supabase`
> - **Password**: `this_password_is_insecure_and_should_be_updated`

You must change these credentials right away for security. (Instructions below)

---

## 7. Securing Your Setup

### 7.1 Update Default Credentials & Secrets

Open `.env` in the `supabase/docker` folder and modify:

1. **Supabase Studio credentials**
   ```bash
   DASHBOARD_USERNAME=<your_secure_dashboard_username>
   DASHBOARD_PASSWORD=<your_secure_dashboard_password>
   ```
2. **JWT Secret**
   ```bash
   JWT_SECRET=<random_40_characters_string>
   ```
3. **Postgres Password**
   ```bash
   POSTGRES_PASSWORD=<super_strong_password>
   ```
4. **Anon and Service Role Keys**\
   You can generate JWT tokens for `ANON_KEY` and `SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` by using a secure tool or the steps described in the official docs.
   ```bash
   ANON_KEY=<generated_anon_jwt>
   SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=<generated_service_jwt>
   ```
5. **Site URL**
   ```bash
   SITE_URL=https://<your-domain-or-ip>
   ```
6. **Pooler Tenant ID**
   ```bash
   POOLER_TENANT_ID=<some-unique-tenant-id>
   ```

### 7.2 SMTP Settings

If you need to send emails (password resets, invitations, etc.), configure your mail server or SMTP provider:

```bash
SMTP_ADMIN_EMAIL=
SMTP_HOST=
SMTP_PORT=
SMTP_USER=
SMTP_PASS=
SMTP_SENDER_NAME=
```

For best deliverability, consider using a service like AWS SES, SendGrid, Mailgun, etc.

### 7.3 Restart Containers to Apply Changes

After updating all environment variables, you must restart the containers:

```bash
docker compose down
docker compose up -d
```

---

## 8. Open Firewall Ports (If Necessary)

If your Ubuntu server has **ufw** or another firewall enabled, you need to allow incoming connections on port **8000** to access Supabase Studio and the APIs:

```bash
sudo ufw allow 8000/tcp
```

You can also check which ports/services are allowed:

```bash
sudo ufw status
```

---

## 9. Connecting to Your Postgres Database

By default, the Supabase Docker setup uses **Supavisor** (a connection pooler). You can connect in two ways:

1. **Session-based** (direct) connection on port `5432`:
   ```bash
   psql "postgres://postgres.your-tenant-id:your-super-secret-and-long-postgres-password@<YOUR_SERVER_IP>:5432/postgres"
   ```
2. **Pooled** (transactional) connection on port `6543`:
   ```bash
   psql "postgres://postgres.your-tenant-id:your-super-secret-and-long-postgres-password@<YOUR_SERVER_IP>:6543/postgres"
   ```

Replace the tenant ID, password, and IP with your own values from your `.env`.

---

## 10. Useful Commands

### 10.1 Check Container Status

```bash
docker compose ps
```

### 10.2 View Logs of a Specific Service

```bash
docker compose logs -f <service-name>
# e.g., docker compose logs -f studio
```

### 10.3 Stop All Services

```bash
docker compose stop
```

### 10.4 Remove All Containers and Volumes

> **Warning**: This will delete all data, including your Postgres database!

```bash
docker compose down -v
rm -rf volumes/db/data/
```

---

## 11. Keeping Supabase Up to Date

The Docker Compose file pins specific versions of each Supabase service. To update to the latest versions:

1. Edit the **image tags** in `docker-compose.yml` (or use the existing pinned versions).
2. Pull the new images:
   ```bash
   docker compose pull
   ```
3. Restart the containers:
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d
   ```

---

## 12. Next Steps

- **Add SSL**: If you have a domain name, you can put a reverse proxy like Nginx or Caddy in front of Supabase and serve HTTPS.
- **Configure a Secrets Manager**: Instead of storing production secrets in `.env`, consider using a secure secrets manager (HashiCorp Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, GCP Secrets Manager, Doppler, Infisical, etc.).
- **Deploy Edge Functions**: Add your custom serverless functions in `volumes/functions/<FUNCTION_NAME>/index.ts`.
- **Configure S3 Storage**: If you need to store files in S3 instead of the local filesystem, adjust the environment variables in the `docker-compose.yml` for the `storage` service.

---

# Summary

1. **Install Docker + Git** on your Ubuntu server.
2. **Clone** the Supabase repo and enter the `docker` directory.
3. **Copy `.env.example` to `.env`** and edit credentials/secrets.
4. **Pull images** with `docker compose pull`.
5. **Start** the stack with `docker compose up -d`.
6. **Access** Supabase Studio at `http://<server-ip>:8000`.
7. **Secure** your setup by changing credentials, secrets, and restricting firewall access.

You should now have a local Supabase instance running and ready for development (or production, once everything is properly secured and configured). If you have further questions or run into any issues, refer to the [official Supabase Docs](https://supabase.com/docs/guides/self-hosting/docker) or reach out to the Supabase community on [Discord](https://discord.com/invite/supabase).

Happy building!

Below is a concise workflow for **backing up your existing Postgres database** and then **importing** it into the new Supabase Postgres instance.

---

## 1. Back up Your Existing Database

1. **List your databases** (optional step) to confirm the names. You can use:
   ```bash
   sudo -u postgres psql -c "\l"
   ```
   or (if you have a specific DB user)
   ```bash
   psql -U <your_db_user> -c "\l"
   ```

2. **Run `pg_dump`** on the database(s) you need to keep. For example:
   ```bash
   # Using the postgres system account
   sudo -u postgres pg_dump -Fc <old_db_name> > /path/to/old_db_backup.dump

   # Alternatively, if you have a specific user:
   pg_dump -U <your_db_user> -Fc <old_db_name> > /path/to/old_db_backup.dump
   ```
   - The `-Fc` flag creates a **custom format** dump file, which you can later restore with `pg_restore`.
   - If you prefer a plain SQL file, omit `-Fc` (i.e., `pg_dump -U <user> <db> > backup.sql`), but the custom format is usually more flexible for partial restores and includes indexes, roles, etc.

3. Make sure your backup file is safely stored somewhere (e.g., your home folder, external disk, or cloud storage).

---

## 2. Stop or Remove the Old Postgres (Optional)

If your goal is to **completely replace** the old Postgres with Supabase’s Dockerized Postgres, you can stop or remove the old Postgres service:

```bash
# Stop the old Postgres service
sudo systemctl stop postgresql
# Or remove (depending on your distribution/package manager)
sudo apt remove postgresql
```

> **Note**: If you're just running both side by side on different ports, you can skip this step. But if port `5432` is already in use, you won't be able to run Supabase's Postgres on the same port unless you stop the old one or adjust ports.

---

## 3. Launch the Supabase Stack

1. **Clone and set up Supabase** if you haven’t already:
   ```bash
   git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/supabase/supabase
   cd supabase/docker
   cp .env.example .env
   docker compose pull
   docker compose up -d
   ```
2. Verify the containers are running:
   ```bash
   docker compose ps
   ```
3. Identify your **Postgres** credentials from `.env`. The key variables are:
   - `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`
   - `POOLER_TENANT_ID`
   - `POSTGRES_PORT` (usually `5432`)
   - Or the session-based vs. pooled ports (commonly `5432` for session-based and `6543` for pooled/transactional).

By default, Supabase sets up **Supavisor** on port `5432` (session-based) or `6543` (pooled). If you prefer to connect *directly* to the Postgres container (bypassing Supavisor), you’ll need to expose the DB container’s port in `docker-compose.yml` (comment out supavisor or change the port mapping).

---

## 4. Restore Your Backup into Supabase

### 4.1 Session-based (Direct) Connection

If you have **session-based** access on port `5432` via Supavisor or via direct Postgres container, do:

```bash
pg_restore -U postgres \
  -d postgres \
  -h <your_server_ip_or_localhost> \
  -p 5432 \
  /path/to/old_db_backup.dump
```

- Replace `postgres` after `-U` with the user you see in the `.env` (often `postgres.your-tenant-id` if using Supavisor).
- If using the direct `postgres` container user, it might just be `postgres`.
- You’ll be prompted for a password (the one set in `.env` under `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`).
- This will restore the contents of your old database into the default `postgres` database in the new Supabase instance.

### 4.2 Alternatively, Plain SQL Restore

If you used a plain `.sql` dump instead of a custom format (`.dump`):

```bash
psql -U postgres \
  -d postgres \
  -h <your_server_ip_or_localhost> \
  -p 5432 \
  -f /path/to/backup.sql
```

---

## 5. Verify the Imported Data

Once the restore finishes:

1. **Connect** to the new Supabase Postgres and check the data:
   ```bash
   psql -U postgres -d postgres -h <your_server_ip> -p 5432
   \dt
   ```
   or
   ```bash
   psql "postgres://postgres:<POSTGRES_PASSWORD>@<SERVER_IP>:5432/postgres"
   ```
   (Adjust your connection string to match your `.env` credentials.)

2. Ensure the tables and data from your old database are present.

---

## 6. Final Tips

- **Supabase Roles**: If your old database had specialized roles, it may require some manual role creation in the new environment. Alternatively, if you used `pg_dumpall` to get roles, you’ll need to apply them carefully.
- **Extensions**: Check if your old database had special extensions that Supabase doesn’t have by default. Install them if needed (e.g., `CREATE EXTENSION <extension_name>;`).
- **Schema Conflicts**: If your old DB uses schemas that Supabase uses (e.g. `public`, `auth`, etc.), ensure there are no naming collisions. You might consider a carefully selective restore (with `--schema` or `--table` flags).
- **Don’t Overwrite Supabase’s System Schema**: Certain schemas like `auth`, `storage`, `extensions` are used internally by Supabase. Don’t drop these or overwrite them unless you know exactly what you’re doing.
- **Database Settings**: If you had specialized `postgresql.conf` or custom performance tweaks, you can incorporate them into the Docker-based Postgres config if necessary.

---

### Quick Reference Commands

1. **Backup**:
   ```bash
   sudo -u postgres pg_dump -Fc old_db > old_db_backup.dump
   ```
2. **Stop old Postgres** (optional):
   ```bash
   sudo systemctl stop postgresql
   ```
3. **Start Supabase**:
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d
   ```
4. **Restore**:
   ```bash
   pg_restore -U postgres -d postgres -h localhost -p 5432 /path/to/old_db_backup.dump
   ```

That’s it! Once you’ve completed these steps, you’ll have all your old data safely imported into the new Supabase Postgres instance.

Below is a step-by-step guide to help you **properly configure** your environment using the variables in your `.env` file. Each section explains which values you must (or should) change, why, and how to generate safe credentials.

---

## 1. Generate Strong Passwords and JWT Secrets

### 1.1 Postgres Password

- **Variable**: `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`
- **What it does**: Password for the `postgres` user in your new Supabase database.
- **Why update**: The default in the example is insecure. Change it to a long, randomly generated password.
- **Example**: `POSTGRES_PASSWORD=Bu7?cD9tAA28pTcJ4tD#LkfiZ`

You can generate secure strings via:

```bash
openssl rand -base64 24
# or use an online password generator
```

### 1.2 JWT Secret

- **Variable**: `JWT_SECRET`
- **What it does**: Used for signing and verifying JWTs in PostgREST, GoTrue, and other services.
- **Why update**: Must be at least 32 characters, random, and not guessable.
- **Example**: `JWT_SECRET=mypersonalsupabasejwtsecretshouldbeatleast32chars`

You can also use:

```bash
openssl rand -hex 40
```

which will generate a 40-character secret, for example.

---

## 2. Generate New API Keys (ANON\_KEY & SERVICE\_ROLE\_KEY)

The keys (`ANON_KEY` and `SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`) in your `.env` are just **demo** values. If you plan on going to production—or even just want a private setup—you must generate new ones.

Supabase typically uses JWTs to encode these keys. You can generate them in many ways:

- Use a library or command-line tool to sign a JWT using your `JWT_SECRET`.
- Or, to keep things simple, you can create dummy placeholders now and rely on the environment to treat them as "private keys."

**Important**: These keys are used by clients and services. The `ANON_KEY` is typically for unprivileged users, and `SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` is for your server or privileged operations. They should be different tokens, both signed with the same `JWT_SECRET`.

**Example**:

```bash
ANON_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6...
SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6...
```

> If you don’t have a convenient way to generate JWTs, you can temporarily keep these placeholders but **never** leave them as the official keys in production.

---

## 3. Secure the Supabase Studio Login

- **Variables**:
  - `DASHBOARD_USERNAME`
  - `DASHBOARD_PASSWORD`
- **Why update**: The default login (`supabase` / `this_password_is_insecure_and_should_be_updated`) is **publicly known**.
- **Example**:
  ```bash
  DASHBOARD_USERNAME=admin
  DASHBOARD_PASSWORD=AnotherLongSecurePassword
  ```

---

## 4. Update Database Connection Info

In most self-hosted setups, you can keep:

```bash
POSTGRES_HOST=db
POSTGRES_DB=postgres
POSTGRES_PORT=5432
```

Unless you have a custom database name or host. Typically, `db` is the name of the Docker service for the database container. If you have an external database, you’d provide a real hostname (like `mydb.example.com`).

---

## 5. Supavisor (Connection Pooler) Configuration

- **Variables**:
  - `POOLER_PROXY_PORT_TRANSACTION=6543`
  - `POOLER_DEFAULT_POOL_SIZE=20`
  - `POOLER_MAX_CLIENT_CONN=100`
  - `POOLER_TENANT_ID=your-tenant-id`
- **Why**: For typical single-tenant usage, you can keep the defaults. However, make sure `POOLER_TENANT_ID` is unique if you plan to run multiple tenants.

**Example**:

```bash
POOLER_TENANT_ID=my-org-1234
```

---

## 6. Kong (API Gateway) Ports

- **Variables**:
  - `KONG_HTTP_PORT=8000`
  - `KONG_HTTPS_PORT=8443`
- **Why**: By default, Supabase routes through the HTTP gateway on port `8000`. If you want to serve over HTTPS, you typically do so behind a reverse proxy (Nginx, Caddy, etc.). If you prefer direct, you can expose `8443` with SSL certificates in Kong, but that requires additional Kong configuration.

---

## 7. PostgREST Configuration

- **Variable**: `PGRST_DB_SCHEMAS=public,storage,graphql_public`
- **What it does**: Defines which Postgres schemas PostgREST will expose in the auto-generated RESTful API.
- **Recommendation**: By default, `public`, `storage`, and `graphql_public` is fine for a typical setup. If you have custom schemas, add them here.

---

## 8. Auth (GoTrue) Configuration

- **Variable**: `SITE_URL=http://localhost:3000`
  - Change to your actual site domain or IP if you’re self-hosting and want OAuth/email confirmations to link properly.
  - **Example**: `SITE_URL=https://mydomain.com`
- **Variable**: `API_EXTERNAL_URL=http://localhost:8000`
  - This is the base URL for the Auth server. Typically pointed at Kong on port `8000`. If you run behind a custom domain, update accordingly.
- **Variable**: `JWT_EXPIRY=3600`
  - Token expiration in seconds. Adjust if your tokens need to last longer or shorter.

### 8.1 Mailer Config (SMTP)

- **Variables**:
  - `SMTP_ADMIN_EMAIL=admin@example.com`
  - `SMTP_HOST=supabase-mail`
  - `SMTP_PORT=2500`
  - `SMTP_USER=fake_mail_user`
  - `SMTP_PASS=fake_mail_password`
  - `SMTP_SENDER_NAME=fake_sender`
- **What it does**: GoTrue uses SMTP settings to send confirmation, recovery, invite, etc.
- **Recommendation**: Put your real SMTP service credentials. E.g., if you have AWS SES, SendGrid, or Mailgun:

  ```bash
  SMTP_ADMIN_EMAIL=admin@mydomain.com
  SMTP_HOST=smtp.sendgrid.net
  SMTP_PORT=587
  SMTP_USER=my_sendgrid_user
  SMTP_PASS=my_sendgrid_pass
  SMTP_SENDER_NAME="My App"
  ```

### 8.2 Enable/Disable Signups

- **Variables**:
  - `ENABLE_EMAIL_SIGNUP=true`
  - `ENABLE_ANONYMOUS_USERS=false`
  - `ENABLE_PHONE_SIGNUP=true`
  - etc.
- **Recommendation**: Tailor these to how you want your app’s user onboarding to work.

---

## 9. Studio (Dashboard)

- **Variables**:
  - `STUDIO_DEFAULT_ORGANIZATION=Default Organization`
  - `STUDIO_DEFAULT_PROJECT=Default Project`
  - `STUDIO_PORT=3000`
  - `SUPABASE_PUBLIC_URL=http://localhost:8000`
- **Note**: The main item to change is `SUPABASE_PUBLIC_URL` to the domain/IP of your Kong gateway. Also, if you want to run the dashboard on a different port or behind a proxy, adjust `STUDIO_PORT`.

---

## 10. Edge Functions (Functions)

- **Variable**: `FUNCTIONS_VERIFY_JWT=false`
- **What it does**: If you set it to `true`, any invocation to your edge functions will be validated with JWT. Keep it `false` if you want open or custom-coded checks.

---

## 11. Logs (Analytics / Logflare)

- **Variables**:
  - `LOGFLARE_LOGGER_BACKEND_API_KEY=your-super-secret-and-long-logflare-key`
  - `LOGFLARE_API_KEY=your-super-secret-and-long-logflare-key`
- **What it does**: Used by the Analytics service for collecting logs. If you are not using the integrated Analytics or Logflare, you can leave these as placeholders. If you do want to use them, get actual keys from your Logflare or Supabase Analytics setup.

---

## 12. Docker Socket Location

- **Variable**: `DOCKER_SOCKET_LOCATION=/var/run/docker.sock`
- **Why**: If you’re using **rootless Docker** or a different Docker setup, the socket location changes, e.g. `/run/user/1000/docker.sock`. Adjust if you see errors about the Docker socket.

---

## 13. Example Final `.env` Snippet

Below is a **sample** `.env` snippet (for illustration only; replace values with your actual secrets):

```dotenv
############

############
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=Bu7?cD9tAA28pTcJ4tD#LkfiZ
JWT_SECRET=63cba0a213489087c87bfe9789afc59b7c8fbadb
ANON_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...
SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...
DASHBOARD_USERNAME=admin
DASHBOARD_PASSWORD=superSafeDashboardPass

MAILER_URLPATHS_CONFIRMATION="/auth/v1/verify"
MAILER_URLPATHS_INVITE="/auth/v1/verify"
MAILER_URLPATHS_RECOVERY="/auth/v1/verify"
MAILER_URLPATHS_EMAIL_CHANGE="/auth/v1/verify"
ENABLE_EMAIL_SIGNUP=true
ENABLE_EMAIL_AUTOCONFIRM=false
SMTP_ADMIN_EMAIL=admin@mydomain.com
SMTP_HOST=smtp.mailgun.org
SMTP_PORT=587
SMTP_USER=my_mailgun_username

SMTP_SENDER_NAME="My App"

############
# Studio
```

---

## 14. Apply and Restart

Once your `.env` is set with these secure and customized values:

1. **Save** the file.

2. **Restart** your services:
   ```bash
   docker compose down
   docker compose up -d
   ```
   This ensures that each container picks up the new environment variables.

3. **Check** logs and health:
   ```bash
   docker compose ps
   docker compose logs -f
   ```
   All containers should report “healthy” if configured properly.

---

# Summary

1. **Change all insecure defaults**: Especially `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`, `JWT_SECRET`, `ANON_KEY`, `SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`, and `DASHBOARD_PASSWORD`.
2. **Set your domain** in `SITE_URL` and possibly `SUPABASE_PUBLIC_URL` for email confirmations, redirects, and the dashboard.
3. **Configure SMTP** if you need email confirmations.
4. **Restart** Docker containers after changes.

Following these steps ensures your environment is both **secure** and **properly aligned** with your use case. You can then start working with your self-hosted Supabase instance safely.

<time datetime="2025-01-19T05:24:56.545Z" title="1/19/2025, 2:24:56 PM">14:24</time>

It looks like the **Analytics** container is trying to connect to the database using a user named **`supabase_admin`** but the password is incorrect (or that user doesn’t yet exist in the DB). In the logs, you’ll see:

```
FATAL:  password authentication failed for user "supabase_admin"
```

By default in newer Supabase Docker setups, the **Analytics** service will connect as `supabase_admin` unless configured otherwise. If your database is only set up with the `postgres` user (the one controlled by `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` in your `.env`), you’ll need to **either**:

1. **Create** a `supabase_admin` user in the database with a matching password, **or**
2. **Tell** the Analytics container to use the existing `postgres` superuser and its password.

Below are two common approaches to fix the mismatch.

---

## Option A: Create a `supabase_admin` User in Your Postgres

1. **Stop** the containers so that you can modify the DB without conflict:

   ```bash
   docker compose down
   ```

2. **Start** the database container alone (so you can run psql inside it):

   ```bash
   docker compose up -d db
   ```

3. **Attach** to the database container and create/alter the `supabase_admin` user:

   ```bash
   docker compose exec db psql -U postgres -d postgres
   ```

   Inside the `psql` shell, run:

   ```sql
   CREATE USER supabase_admin WITH SUPERUSER LOGIN PASSWORD 'YOUR_PASSWORD_HERE';
   \q
   ```

   > Make sure `'YOUR_PASSWORD_HERE'` exactly matches the password that Analytics is trying to use. Typically, Analytics looks in the `.env` or docker-compose for something like `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` or a dedicated variable for `supabase_admin`.
   >
   > If `supabase_admin` already exists, just do:
   >
   > ```sql
   > ALTER USER supabase_admin WITH PASSWORD 'YOUR_PASSWORD_HERE';
   > ```

4. **Stop** the DB again and **bring up** the entire Supabase stack:

   ```bash
   docker compose down
   docker compose up -d
   ```

5. **Check logs** to ensure Analytics can now authenticate:

   ```bash
   docker compose logs -f supabase-analytics
   ```

   You should no longer see `FATAL: password authentication failed for user "supabase_admin"`.

With that, you’ll have a dedicated user named `supabase_admin` in the database. The Analytics container should connect without error.

---

## Option B: Reconfigure Analytics to Use the `postgres` User

Instead of creating a separate `supabase_admin` user, you can direct the Analytics container to connect as `postgres` (the same superuser that other services might use). This depends on how the analytics container environment variables are set. For example, in recent Supabase versions, your `docker-compose.yml` or `.env` might have lines like:

```yaml
analytics:
  environment:
    DB_HOST: db
    DB_NAME: _supabase
    DB_USER: supabase_admin     <-- Change this to "postgres"
    DB_PASSWORD: some-password
```

or:

```bash
SUPABASE_ANALYTICS_DB_USER=supabase_admin
SUPABASE_ANALYTICS_DB_PASSWORD=...
```

1. **Find** where the Analytics container is specifying `supabase_admin`. This could be in:
   - `docker-compose.yml` under `services.analytics.environment`, **or**
   - The shared `.env` (e.g., lines like `DB_USER=supabase_admin`).

2. **Change** that user to `postgres` and the password to match the `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` you set in your `.env`, for example:

   ```bash
   DB_USER=postgres
   DB_PASSWORD=your-super-secret-and-long-postgres-password
   ```

3. **Redeploy** your containers:

   ```bash
   docker compose down
   docker compose up -d
   ```

4. **Confirm** that analytics logs show a successful connection (no more `invalid_password` errors).

---

## Why This Happens

- In some Supabase versions, the **Analytics** container tries to connect with a specialized superuser named `supabase_admin`.
- If that user hasn’t been created in the database or if the password doesn’t match, you’ll see `FATAL 28P01 (invalid_password)`.
- Either adding that user to the DB with the correct password (Option A) or telling Analytics to use the existing `postgres` user (Option B) will fix the issue.

**Pro Tip**: If you’re running a newer version of Supabase that references a `_supabase` database or a `supabase_admin` role, it’s best to keep those consistent by actually creating that user in Postgres. That way, your logs and roles match the default “best practices” from the official Docker Compose stack.

---

### Quick Fix Summary

1. **Create or alter** the `supabase_admin` user to match the password from your `.env` and analytics environment (most common fix).
2. **Or** change the Analytics config to use `postgres` + `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`.
3. **Restart** and confirm logs are clean.

After this, your Analytics service should be able to connect without throwing the **“password authentication failed”** error.

You're seeing the error:

```
ERROR:  permission denied to create role
DETAIL:  Only roles with the SUPERUSER attribute may create roles with the SUPERUSER attribute.
```

because the user you're currently logged in as (`postgres`) **isn't actually a superuser** in your Supabase Docker setup. By default, many Supabase Docker stacks make **`supabase_admin`** the superuser instead of the `postgres` role.

Below are several ways to solve this, depending on whether you have data you need to preserve.

---

## 1. Find Out Which User Is the Real Superuser

1. **Check** your `.env` or `docker-compose.yml`:

   - Look for:
     ```bash
     POSTGRES_USER=supabase_admin
     POSTGRES_PASSWORD=some-supersecret
     ```
     or
     ```bash
     POSTGRES_USER=postgres
     # but maybe there's also a SUPABASE_ADMIN_PASSWORD or something similar
     ```
2. **Inspect** the roles inside the running DB container:

   ```bash
   docker compose exec db psql -U postgres -d postgres -c "SELECT rolname, rolsuper FROM pg_roles;"
   ```

   - If it shows `supabase_admin | t` and `postgres | f`, then `supabase_admin` is the superuser and `postgres` is not.
   - If `postgres` is also `false` for `rolsuper`, that means it cannot create superuser roles.

---

## 2. Log in as the Actual Superuser (`supabase_admin`)

If **`supabase_admin`** is listed as a superuser in the output of the query above, you can log in with it directly instead of `postgres`. For example:

```bash
# For Linux/macOS, you can set PGPASSWORD inline or you'll be prompted.
PGPASSWORD=the_admin_password_you_set_in_env \
docker compose exec db psql \
  -U supabase_admin \
  -h localhost \
  -d postgres
```

> **Tip**: If you get a prompt for a password, enter the same one from your `.env` file under `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` (if your `.env` says `POSTGRES_USER=supabase_admin`). Or if there's a separate environment variable for `SUPABASE_ADMIN_PASSWORD`, use that one.

Once you're connected as `supabase_admin`, you can create or modify other superusers:

```sql
CREATE USER admin WITH SUPERUSER LOGIN PASSWORD 'somepassword';
```

---

## 3. Make `postgres` a Superuser (If You Prefer)

If you want the `postgres` role to be superuser again (like in vanilla Postgres):

1. **Log in** as the real superuser (likely `supabase_admin`), as shown above.
2. Run:
   ```sql
   ALTER ROLE postgres WITH SUPERUSER;
   ```
3. Then exit and reconnect as `postgres` if you wish.

---

## 4. If You Have No Data to Preserve (Fresh Setup)

If this is a new Supabase install and you're not worried about **losing data**, the simplest solution can be:

1. **Stop and remove** the entire Supabase stack plus volumes (so that Postgres re-initializes with your newly configured env):
   ```bash
   docker compose down -v
   ```
   > **Warning**: `-v` removes volumes, which **destroys all data** in the database.
2. **Make sure** your `.env` has the settings you want—commonly:
   ```bash
   POSTGRES_USER=postgres
   POSTGRES_PASSWORD=some-strong-password
   ```
   or
   ```bash
   POSTGRES_USER=supabase_admin
   POSTGRES_PASSWORD=some-strong-password
   ```
   and ensure `supabase_admin` is recognized as superuser if that’s how Supabase sets it up.
3. **Spin up** fresh:
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d
   ```
4. Now your DB container will create the superuser role as specified in your `.env`.

---

## 5. Summary of Key Points

- **Check** which role is superuser (often `supabase_admin` in newer Supabase Docker stacks).
- **Log in** as that role to create or alter other superusers.
- **`postgres`** may **not** be a superuser in the Supabase Docker image by default.
- If you **don’t have important data**, re-initialize with the environment variables you prefer.

Once you log in with the actual superuser, you’ll be able to create or modify roles as needed (e.g., `CREATE USER admin WITH SUPERUSER`). After that, your analytics, backups, or any role-based commands should work without the “permission denied” error.

You’re running into the common Supabase situation where the **Analytics** container expects to connect as a user named `supabase_admin`, but the default Postgres user in your Docker container may be `postgres`, and/or `postgres` might not be a superuser. In Supabase’s Docker setup, one user is typically designated as a **superuser**, and by default, the Analytics container tries to use `supabase_admin` with `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`.

Below is how to align your database roles so that the Analytics container can connect without error:

---

## 1. Understand the Defaults in This Docker Setup

- **Database container** (service: `db` in `docker-compose.yml`)
  - Usually sets up a superuser. In *older* or *standard* Postgres images, that superuser is named `postgres`.
  - In **some** Supabase images, the superuser is named `supabase_admin`.

- **Analytics container** (service: `analytics`)
  - By default, it tries to connect to the `_supabase` database with the user `supabase_admin` and password `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`.
  - Fails if `supabase_admin` doesn’t exist or if the password is wrong, or if `supabase_admin` is not actually a superuser.

---

## 2. Check Which Role Is the Actual Superuser

First, see who is *really* a superuser in your running database:

1. Start only the DB container so you can inspect the roles:
   ```bash
   docker compose down
   docker compose up -d db
   ```
2. List roles inside the container:
   ```bash
   docker compose exec db psql -U postgres -d postgres -c "SELECT rolname, rolsuper FROM pg_roles;"
   ```

Look for something like:

```
  rolname       | rolsuper
----------------+----------
 postgres       | f
 supabase_admin | t
 ...
(etc.)
```

- If you see `supabase_admin | t`, that means `supabase_admin` **is** the superuser, while `postgres` is **not**.
- If instead you see `postgres | t`, that means `postgres` is the superuser.
- There might also be an `authenticator` role with no superuser privileges.

---

## 3. Log In With the Actual Superuser

Once you know who the superuser is:

1. **If `supabase_admin` is the superuser**
   - Try logging in with that role and the password in `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`:
     ```bash
     docker compose exec db psql -U supabase_admin -d postgres
     ```
     - If it prompts for a password, enter the value of `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` from your `.env`.
   - Once inside the `psql` shell, you can create or modify roles as needed.

2. **If `postgres` is the superuser**
   - Just keep using `psql -U postgres -d postgres` as you did—then you can create/alter the `supabase_admin` role or any other roles as needed.

---

## 4. Make Sure `supabase_admin` Exists With the Right Password

If `supabase_admin` doesn’t exist or is not superuser, create or alter it from `psql`:

```sql
CREATE ROLE supabase_admin WITH SUPERUSER LOGIN PASSWORD 'YOUR_STRONG_PASSWORD';
-- or if it already exists, just:
ALTER ROLE supabase_admin WITH SUPERUSER LOGIN PASSWORD 'YOUR_STRONG_PASSWORD';
```

> **Important**: That password **must match** your `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` in the `.env` file if you want the analytics container’s default config to work. By default, analytics uses:
>
> ```yaml
> environment:
>   DB_USERNAME: supabase_admin
>   DB_PASSWORD: ${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}
>   ...
> ```

Once the role is set up correctly, **exit** the `psql` shell.

---

## 5. Spin Up the Full Supabase Stack

Now that you’ve fixed the database roles:

```bash
docker compose down
docker compose up -d
```

Check logs:

```bash
docker compose logs -f analytics
```

You should no longer see the “password authentication failed for user `supabase_admin`” errors. The Analytics container should connect properly to the `_supabase` database.

---

## 6. (Optional) If You Don’t Care About Existing Data

If it’s a **fresh** setup and you can safely lose all data, you can let the Supabase Postgres container **re-initialize** everything automatically:

1. Stop and **remove** volumes (this deletes your entire DB):
   ```bash
   docker compose down -v
   ```
2. **Ensure** your `.env` or `docker-compose.yml` is set up with the correct superuser name and password (e.g., `POSTGRES_USER=supabase_admin`, `POSTGRES_PASSWORD=...`).
3. Bring everything up fresh:
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d
   ```

This approach can be simpler if you just started and have no data, letting Supabase’s init scripts create the right roles automatically.

---

## 7. Summary of Key Steps

1. **Identify** which role is superuser by querying `pg_roles`.
2. **Log in** as that superuser (likely `supabase_admin`) to create or fix the `supabase_admin` role.
3. Make sure **`supabase_admin`** has the same password as `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` in your `.env` (or update the analytics container config to match whatever password you gave `supabase_admin`).
4. **Restart** the containers and confirm no more authentication errors.

With that, the Analytics container will finally connect without the “invalid\_password” issue.

<time datetime="2025-01-19T07:37:33.173Z" title="1/19/2025, 4:37:33 PM">16:37</time>

The error **“database `_supabase` does not exist”** means that your Analytics container expects to connect to a database named `_supabase` (as shown in the logs and environment variables), but that database was never created in Postgres. By default, Supabase’s self-hosted Analytics tries to use `_supabase` for storing logs.

Below are several ways to resolve it, depending on whether or not you can afford to reset (destroy) the current database.

---

## 1. Create the `_supabase` Database Manually (Non-Destructive)

If you **already have** data in your Postgres container that you don’t want to lose, the easiest solution is to manually create `_supabase` and run any necessary migrations:

1. **Check** that the database container is running:
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d db
   ```

2. **Log in** as a superuser (likely `supabase_admin`) to the main Postgres database:
   ```bash
   docker compose exec db psql -U supabase_admin -d postgres
   ```
   If you get a password prompt, use the same password set as `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` in your `.env`.

3. **Create** the `_supabase` database:
   ```sql
   CREATE DATABASE _supabase WITH OWNER supabase_admin;
   ```
   Then `\c _supabase` to connect to it if you want:
   ```sql
   \c _supabase;
   ```

4. **(Optional) Run the `_supabase` migrations** that Supabase normally runs automatically. You should have a file named `97-_supabase.sql` in `volumes/db/`. You can run it manually:
   ```bash
   \i /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/migrations/97-_supabase.sql
   ```
   or in your Docker environment, something like:
   ```bash
   docker compose exec db psql -U supabase_admin -d _supabase -f /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/migrations/97-_supabase.sql
   ```
   This ensures the `_supabase` schema and tables exist for analytics.

5. **Exit** psql, then **bring up** the entire stack:
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d
   ```

6. **Check logs** to confirm the analytics container connects properly:
   ```bash
   docker compose logs -f analytics
   ```
   You should see successful migrations or “healthy” status rather than “database `_supabase` does not exist.”

---

## 2. Let Supabase Auto-Initialize (Destructive: Wipes All Data)

If this is a fresh deployment and you have **no data to preserve**, the most straightforward fix is to let Supabase’s entrypoint scripts create `_supabase` automatically. Essentially, you remove the old volume and let the container re-run its `.sql` migrations from scratch:

1. **Stop** the containers:
   ```bash
   docker compose down
   ```

2. **Remove volumes** (this destroys **all** data in the DB!):
   ```bash
   docker compose down -v
   ```

3. **Ensure** your `.env` and `docker-compose.yml` lines that mount `volumes/db/_supabase.sql:/docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/migrations/97-_supabase.sql` are present (they appear to be in your file).

4. **Bring** everything back up:
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d
   ```

5. The database container will now re-initialize, automatically run the migration scripts (including `97-_supabase.sql`), and create `_supabase`. Check:

   ```bash
   docker compose logs -f db
   ```

   You should see it running the migration scripts, ending with something like `Database system is ready to accept connections`.

6. **Verify** analytics in the logs:
   ```bash
   docker compose logs -f analytics
   ```
   No more “database `_supabase` does not exist” errors.

---

## 3. (Advanced) Use a Different Database Name for Analytics

In your `docker-compose.yml`, the `analytics` service has:

```yaml
environment:
  DB_DATABASE: _supabase
  POSTGRES_BACKEND_URL: postgresql://supabase_admin:${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}@${POSTGRES_HOST}:${POSTGRES_PORT}/_supabase
  ...
```

You could point analytics at an existing database (e.g., the default `postgres`) and a separate schema (`_analytics`). For instance:

```yaml
environment:
  DB_DATABASE: postgres
  POSTGRES_BACKEND_URL: postgresql://supabase_admin:${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}@db:5432/postgres
  DB_SCHEMA: _analytics
  POSTGRES_BACKEND_SCHEMA: _analytics
```

But the standard approach is to keep logs in a dedicated `_supabase` DB so they’re separate from your main application data. That’s what the default Docker Compose expects.

---

## Summary

- Your Analytics container is trying to connect to `_supabase`.
- **If you have data** you want to keep, manually create `_supabase` and run the `_supabase.sql` migration script.
- **If you have no data** to keep, you can remove volumes, and let Supabase’s docker-entrypoint scripts automatically initialize everything, including `_supabase`.

Once `_supabase` exists and the analytics migrations are applied, the error **“database `_supabase` does not exist”** will go away.

3. **Bring everything up** again:


   You should see Postgres running the scripts in `/docker-entrypoint-initdb.d` again and populating the database with Supabase’s defaults (e.g., `_supabase` database, `_analytics` schema, etc.).

If you **already have** data you do not want to lose, you can **manually** perform the needed steps (e.g., creating `_supabase`, `_analytics`, certain roles) by connecting to Postgres directly. For example:

When you see **“Kong Error: Invalid authentication credentials”** while trying to access Supabase (usually at `http://<your-host>:8000`), it almost always means that **Kong’s basic authentication** is rejecting the username/password you’re providing. Here’s how to fix it:

---

## 1. Understand How Supabase’s “Dashboard” Authentication Works

- Supabase uses **Kong** (an API gateway) to protect access to the dashboard (Studio) with **basic auth**.
- By default, the credentials come from `.env` variables:
  ```bash
  DASHBOARD_USERNAME=admin
  DASHBOARD_PASSWORD=some_password
  ```
- Alternatively, they could be **hard-coded** in `volumes/api/kong.yml`. If your setup has lines like:
  ```yaml
  basicauth_credentials:
    - consumer: DASHBOARD
      username: supabase
      password: this_password_is_insecure_and_should_be_updated
  ```
  then these are the actual credentials unless you’ve overridden them via environment variables.

When you visit `http://<SERVER_IP>:8000`, Kong will prompt for **basic auth**. If the credentials you enter don’t match the stored username/password, you’ll see “Invalid authentication credentials.”

---

## 2. Common Causes and Fixes

### Cause A: Environment Variables Not Applied

If you **updated** `.env` with new values (e.g., `DASHBOARD_USERNAME=admin`, `DASHBOARD_PASSWORD=1`) but Kong **still** says “Invalid authentication credentials”:

1. **Confirm** `.env` has your desired values:
   ```bash
   grep -E 'DASHBOARD_USERNAME|DASHBOARD_PASSWORD' .env
   ```
2. **Restart** the containers so Kong picks up the changes:
   ```bash
   docker compose down
   docker compose up -d
   ```
3. **Try logging in** again. If you have trouble getting a new login prompt in your browser (because basic auth credentials can be cached), open an **incognito** window or a different browser to ensure you’re asked for credentials again.

### Cause B: Kong’s Config File Hard-Coded

Supabase’s default `kong.yml` can hard-code credentials if it doesn’t reference environment variables. Look at `volumes/api/kong.yml` for something like this:

```yaml
basicauth_credentials:
  - consumer: DASHBOARD
    username: supabase
    password: this_password_is_insecure_and_should_be_updated
```

- If you see **literal** credentials there, that’s what Kong is using.
- To fix it:
  1. Either **edit** `kong.yml` directly with your own username/password, **or**
  2. Change them to reference the environment variables. For example:
     ```yaml
     basicauth_credentials:
       - consumer: DASHBOARD
         username: ${DASHBOARD_USERNAME}
         password: ${DASHBOARD_PASSWORD}
     ```
  3. Then run:
     ```bash
     docker compose down
     docker compose up -d
     ```
  4. Now Kong should respect your `.env` values for basic auth.

### Cause C: Mixing Up Studio Login vs. Basic Auth

- The initial basic auth popup is from **Kong**. You must use `DASHBOARD_USERNAME` / `DASHBOARD_PASSWORD`.
- **Inside** the Supabase Studio (the web UI after you pass basic auth), you’ll see another login form for your database connection if needed. That’s **not** the same as the Kong credentials.
- Make sure you’re using the correct **basic auth** credentials for the gateway. After that, the default “passwordless” sign-in to Studio is typically handled by that same basic auth (unless you changed it).

### Cause D: Browser Credential Cache

Once a browser sends incorrect basic auth credentials, it may **cache** them. Try:

- Using an **Incognito** or **Private** browsing window, or
- Clearing saved credentials in your browser.

Then load `http://<your-host>:8000` again so it re-prompts for username/password.

---

## 3. Quick Checklist

1. **Check `.env`** for `DASHBOARD_USERNAME` / `DASHBOARD_PASSWORD`.
2. **Check `volumes/api/kong.yml`** if it uses environment variables or a hard-coded user/pass.
3. **Restart** containers after any changes:
   ```bash
   docker compose down && docker compose up -d
   ```
4. **Test** the login in an incognito window to ensure you’re prompted for fresh credentials.
5. Enter the **exact** same credentials from `.env` (or `kong.yml` if hard-coded).

If everything is consistent and you’re using the right credentials in the basic auth prompt, Kong should accept them and you’ll no longer see **“Invalid authentication credentials.”**

Below is a concise guide on how to connect to your Supabase Postgres database **from outside** Docker, for example with a local psql client or in your application’s connection string.

---

## 1. Identify the Database Ports

Your `docker-compose.yml` includes the following snippet for **Supavisor** (the connection pooler):

```yaml
supavisor:
  ...
  ports:
    - "5432:5432"
    - "6543:6543"
```

This means:

- **Port 5432** on your host machine forwards to port 5432 in the container (often used for "session-based" connections).
- **Port 6543** on your host machine forwards to port 6543 in the container (often used for "transaction-based" or “pooled” connections).

You can use **either** port, but 5432 is a straightforward default for most Postgres clients.

---

## 2. Determine the Credentials

From the environment variables in your Docker Compose, we see several references to:

- **Database name**: `POSTGRES_DB=supabase`
- **Password**: `POSTGRES_PASSWORD=supabase`
- **Likely user**: `postgres` or `supabase_admin` (each with password `supabase`)

For example:

```yaml
db:
  ...
  environment:
    POSTGRES_DB: "supabase"
    POSTGRES_PASSWORD: "supabase"
    # default superuser is often 'postgres' or 'supabase_admin'
    ...
```

Many of the services specify `DB_USER` as `supabase_admin` or `postgres`. In this setup, **both** may exist; if you’re unsure which is superuser, you can test either user from psql. Often, `postgres` is either not superuser or is overshadowed by `supabase_admin`—but from a client standpoint, you just need a valid account with the correct password.

---

## 3. Example Connection Strings

### 3.1 Session-based Connection on Port 5432

```bash
psql "postgres://supabase_admin:supabase@<HOST_IP_OR_DOMAIN>:5432/supabase"
```

or

```bash
psql -h <HOST_IP_OR_DOMAIN> -p 5432 -d supabase -U supabase_admin
# Password: supabase
```

Replace `<HOST_IP_OR_DOMAIN>` with the **IP or domain** of your server running Docker.

### 3.2 Transaction-based Connection on Port 6543

If you prefer the pooled port (sometimes used to handle large numbers of short-lived connections):

```bash
psql "postgres://supabase_admin:supabase@<HOST_IP_OR_DOMAIN>:6543/supabase"
```

or

```bash
psql -h <HOST_IP_OR_DOMAIN> -p 6543 -d supabase -U supabase_admin
# Password: supabase
```

---

## 4. Confirm the User and Password

If you get “password authentication failed,” it may mean the database user doesn’t match the password or that a different user is actually the superuser. If so:

1. Look at `POSTGRES_USER` or any references in `docker-compose.yml`.
2. Look at the volumes under `db` to see if you’ve run any initialization scripts that create additional users/roles.
3. You can also attach to the `db` container and list roles:

   ```bash
   # From your host shell:
   docker compose exec db psql -U postgres -d supabase

   -- Then inside psql:
   \du
   ```

   That shows which users exist and whether they are superuser. You might see `postgres` or `supabase_admin` listed. If only one is superuser, use that one (plus the password from `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`).

---

## 5. Connecting From Your Application

If you’re using a programming language or framework, you’d set the connection string similarly:

```env
DATABASE_URL=postgres://supabase_admin:supabase@<HOST_IP_OR_DOMAIN>:5432/supabase
```

or for the pooled port:

```env
DATABASE_URL=postgres://supabase_admin:supabase@<HOST_IP_OR_DOMAIN>:6543/supabase
```

Check your framework’s docs for how to supply the connection URL (e.g., an ORM config file, an `.env` variable, etc.).

---

## 6. Common Pitfalls

1. **Firewalls**: Ensure your server’s firewall (e.g., ufw or security groups) allows inbound connections on port 5432 (and/or 6543).
2. **User vs. Password Mismatch**: Double-check that the user you’re using actually has the same password as set in your `.env` or Docker Compose.
3. **Localhost vs. External**: If you’re running everything on your own dev machine with Docker, you can typically connect to `localhost` on port 5432/6543. If this is a remote server, use the server’s public IP or domain.
4. **Pooler vs. Direct**: In some Supabase setups, the direct Postgres container might also expose a different port if you’ve overridden it in your Docker Compose. By default, however, we rely on Supavisor on port 5432 for a simpler setup.

---

### Quick Summary

- **Host**: `localhost` (if Docker is local) or `<your-remote-server-IP-or-domain>`
- **Port**: `5432` (session-based) or `6543` (transaction-based)
- **Database**: `supabase`
- **User**: `supabase_admin` (commonly) or `postgres`
- **Password**: `supabase` (based on `POSTGRES_PASSWORD=supabase`)

Connect with:

```bash
psql "postgres://supabase_admin:supabase@<HOST>:5432/supabase"
```

That’s all it takes to link your external client or app to your self-hosted Supabase database.

When using Docker’s CLI directly, the command `docker logs` **only** supports logging from a **single container** at a time. If you try `docker logs all` or `docker logs`, Docker won’t know which single container you want logs from.

Below are some ways to view your Docker logs more easily:

---

## 1. View Logs for a Single Container

First, identify the container name or ID:

```bash
docker ps
```

Then select the container you want, for example `supabase-auth`. Run:

```bash
docker logs supabase-auth
```

- **Add the `-f` (follow) flag** to stream logs in real-time:
  ```bash
  docker logs -f supabase-auth
  ```
- **Press `Ctrl + C`** to stop following logs.

---

## 2. View Logs for Multiple Containers in a Docker **Compose** Project

If you’re inside the directory that has your **docker-compose.yml**, you can use `docker compose logs`. For example:

```bash
# Shows the logs for all containers in the current docker-compose project.
docker compose logs

# Follow logs (live) for all containers in this project.
docker compose logs -f

# Or limit to a specific service (e.g., the "auth" service):
docker compose logs -f auth
```

This is typically the easiest way to view logs for a multi-container project like Supabase.

---

## 3. View Logs for *All* Running Containers (Pure Docker)

If you really want logs from **every** running container on your system (not just one Compose project), you can chain commands. For example:

```bash
docker logs -f $(docker ps -q)
```

This will:

1. `docker ps -q` lists all running container IDs.
2. Pass them to `docker logs -f`, printing all logs in one stream.

Be aware that this can be **very** noisy if you have many containers.

---

## 4. Summary

- **`docker logs <container>`**: Standard Docker CLI for one container.
- **`docker compose logs`**: For a Docker Compose stack, easily see logs for multiple services, with `-f` to follow.
- **`docker logs -f $(docker ps -q)`**: Hacky approach to see logs for every container on the host (not just the Compose ones).

Most Supabase users prefer:

```bash
cd /path/to/supabase/docker
docker compose logs -f
```

to see all logs from the Supabase stack in one place. Then you can watch for errors or see the containers spin up in real time.

Below are the typical ways to resolve this:

---

## Option A: Create/Alter the `supabase_auth_admin` User in the Database

1. **Stop** other Supabase containers so nothing else conflicts:
   ```bash
   docker compose down
   docker compose up -d db
   ```

2. **Log into** Postgres as a superuser (likely `supabase_admin`):
   ```bash
   docker compose exec db psql -U supabase_admin -d supabase
   ```
   (If prompted for a password, use what is in `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` from `.env` or your Compose.)

3. **Create** or **alter** the `supabase_auth_admin` role with the matching password. For example, if your Compose file suggests the password is `supabase`, do:

   ```sql
   CREATE ROLE supabase_auth_admin WITH LOGIN PASSWORD 'supabase';
   -- or if it already exists:
   -- ALTER ROLE supabase_auth_admin WITH PASSWORD 'supabase';

   -- Optionally give privileges if needed
   GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON DATABASE supabase TO supabase_auth_admin;
   ```

4. **Exit** psql with `\q`.

5. **Bring up** everything again:
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d
   ```

6. **Check** logs:
   ```bash
   docker compose logs -f auth
   ```
   You should no longer see “password authentication failed for user supabase\_auth\_admin.”

---

## Option B: Change the Auth Container to Use a Different (Existing) User

If you don’t want to bother creating `supabase_auth_admin`, you can have the Auth service connect as a user that already exists and matches your environment. For instance, some setups only use `postgres` or `supabase_admin` with a known password (`supabase`). You can do this by editing the relevant environment variable in your Docker Compose file for the `auth` service:

```yaml
auth:
  environment:
    GOTRUE_DB_DATABASE_URL: "postgres://postgres:supabase@db:5432/supabase"
    # or ...
    # GOTRUE_DB_DATABASE_URL: "postgres://supabase_admin:supabase@db:5432/supabase"
```

Then:

1. **docker compose down**
2. **docker compose up -d**
3. Confirm logs for `auth` show a healthy connection.

---

## Option C: Start Fresh (Destructive, Wipes All Data)

If this is a brand-new deployment, you can remove volumes so the database re-initializes with all the roles that Supabase typically creates:

```bash
docker compose down -v  # removes all volumes, including your DB data
docker compose up -d
```

The official scripts usually create roles like `supabase_auth_admin`, `supabase_admin`, etc., automatically. But **be careful**—this **destroys all existing DB data**.

---

## Summary

- Your Auth container is configured to use `supabase_auth_admin` but the DB doesn’t have that user (or the password doesn’t match).
- **Either** create the missing user with matching credentials (**Option A**), **change** the Docker Compose config to use an existing user (**Option B**), or re-initialize your DB if it’s a fresh setup (**Option C**).

Once the user and password align, Auth will successfully migrate and connect to your Postgres without the `FATAL: password authentication failed` error.

The error:

```
must be owner of function uid (SQLSTATE 42501)
```

means the **Auth** service is attempting to `CREATE OR REPLACE` a Postgres function named `uid()` (in the `auth` schema), but the **database role** running the migration **does not own** that existing function and doesn’t have permission to modify it.

In Postgres, only the function’s owner (or a superuser) can do a `CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION`. Since GoTrue (the Auth service) is running migrations as `supabase_auth_admin` (or whichever user is set in `GOTRUE_DB_DATABASE_URL`), it fails if `supabase_auth_admin` does not already own the existing function.

Below are a few ways to fix it:

---

## 1. Make `supabase_auth_admin` Own the Existing Function

If you want to keep using `supabase_auth_admin` for Auth migrations, you can **transfer ownership** of the `uid()` function (and possibly `role()` as well) to `supabase_auth_admin`. For example:

1. **Stop** other Supabase containers (so they don’t interfere):
   ```bash
   docker compose down
   docker compose up -d db
   ```
2. **Connect** to Postgres as a superuser—likely `supabase_admin`:
   ```bash
   docker compose exec db psql -U supabase_admin -d supabase
   ```
3. **Check** which user owns the function:

   ```sql
   \df+ auth.uid
   ```

   This will show you the function’s owner.
4. **Transfer ownership** to `supabase_auth_admin`:
   ```sql
   ALTER FUNCTION auth.uid() OWNER TO supabase_auth_admin;
   ALTER FUNCTION auth.role() OWNER TO supabase_auth_admin;
   ```
   > If those functions do not exist or are spelled differently, adjust accordingly. Also, do this for any function the Auth migrations are trying to overwrite (like `auth.role()`).
5. **Exit** psql (`\q`), then restart the rest of the containers:
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d
   ```
6. **Check** logs again:
   ```bash
   docker compose logs -f auth
   ```
   If the ownership was transferred, the migration should now succeed.

---

## 2. Use a Superuser for the Auth Migrations

Another approach is to let the Auth migrations run as a **superuser** that can `CREATE OR REPLACE` functions without ownership issues:

1. In your `docker-compose.yml`, edit `GOTRUE_DB_DATABASE_URL` for the `auth` service to use your superuser (e.g. `postgres` or `supabase_admin` if that’s actually superuser) and the correct password.\
   For example:
   ```yaml
   auth:
     environment:
       GOTRUE_DB_DATABASE_URL: "postgres://postgres:YOUR_PASSWORD@db:5432/supabase"
       # or
       # GOTRUE_DB_DATABASE_URL: "postgres://supabase_admin:YOUR_PASSWORD@db:5432/supabase"
   ```
2. **Restart**:
   ```bash
   docker compose down
   docker compose up -d
   ```
3. Now the Auth migrations run as a role with enough privileges to `CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION` no matter who owns it.

---

## 3. Drop Existing Functions Before Migrations (Less Common)

If these functions are leftover from a previous partial install and you don’t care about them, you could **drop** them so the migration can re-create them from scratch:

1. Stop containers except DB:
   ```bash
   docker compose down
   docker compose up -d db
   ```
2. Connect to DB as superuser:
   ```bash
   docker compose exec db psql -U supabase_admin -d supabase
   ```
3. Drop the old functions:
   ```sql
   DROP FUNCTION IF EXISTS auth.uid();
   DROP FUNCTION IF EXISTS auth.role();
   ```
4. **Exit** psql and bring up the stack again:
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d
   ```
5. The Auth container’s migration scripts should now create those functions with the correct owner.

---

## 4. Summary of Solutions

- **Change function owner** to the role used by Auth (`supabase_auth_admin`) so the migration can run.
- **Use a superuser** in `GOTRUE_DB_DATABASE_URL` so you don’t run into ownership issues.
- **Drop** conflicting existing functions if you don’t need them.

Once the role performing Auth migrations has ownership or superuser privileges, the “must be owner of function uid” error will disappear, and your Auth container should start successfully.

When you see:

```
sh: 1: less: not found
```

it’s just **psql** trying to pipe command output to the default pager (`less`)—which isn’t installed in the container image. The query/command actually completed, but psql can’t page/scroll the output.

You have a few quick workarounds:

---

## 1. Turn Off Paging in psql

From within the psql session, run:

```sql
\pset pager off
```

Then try your command again:

```sql
\df+ auth.uid
```

Now psql will just print all output without trying to invoke `less`.

---

## 2. Use a Different Pager

If `more` is installed, or if you want to pipe directly to `cat`:

```sql
\setenv PAGER 'cat'
```

Then:

```sql
\df+ auth.uid
```

will dump the output immediately without paging.

---

## 3. Install `less` in the Container (Not Persistent)

If you **really** want to install `less` inside that container, you can. But note that changes inside containers are lost if you rebuild or update the image. For example:

```bash
docker exec -it supabase-db bash
apt-get update && apt-get install -y less
exit
docker compose exec db psql -U supabase_admin -d supabase
```

Now `\df+ auth.uid` will work with paging. But again, this is ephemeral if the container is ever recreated.

---

## Which Approach to Choose

- If you just need to see the function details once or twice, **Option 1 (turn off pager)** is simplest.
- If you frequently need paging output, you can **set a different pager** or do a one-time install of `less` each time you start the container.

Either way, your Postgres commands (`ALTER FUNCTION …`) already succeeded, and the absence of `less` doesn’t affect database functionality—just the ability to page large query output within psql.
